> A honey glaze may sound like something that goes with dessert, but mild-tasting pork loves a sweet sauce too... especially one that has a few savory elements in it for contrast. In this recipe, you'll be folding an extra-large drizzle of honey into a rich, savory pan sauce, then spooning it onto pork tenderloin (and the roasted potatoes and broccoli served alongside, if you like).

== Roasted Potatoes ==

Adjust racks to top and middle positions and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @Yukon Gold Potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack, tossing halfway through, until lightly browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

== Pork and Broccoli ==

While potatoes roast, pat @pork tenderloin{12%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large #pan{} over medium heat. Add pork and sear, turning occasionally, until browned all over, ~{4-8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and mince half the @garlic{1%clove} (all for 4 servings).

Once pork is browned, transfer to one side of a second baking sheet.

Cut @broccoli florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Toss with a drizzle of @olive oil{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{} on opposite side of baking sheet from pork.

Transfer sheet with pork and broccoli to middle rack. Roast until pork is cooked through and broccoli is tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Once pork is done, transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest. Thinly slice crosswise.

== Pan Sauce ==

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in pan used for pork over medium heat. Add minced garlic and @dried thyme{1%tsp}; cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in @chicken stock concentrate{2}, @honey{2%tsp}, and @water{1/4%cup} (1/3 cup for 4 servings). Simmer, scraping up any browned bits from bottom of pan, until sauce has reduced and thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @butter{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4) until melted. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> TIP: If sauce seems too thick, stir in a splash or two of water.

== To Serve ==

Divide pork, broccoli, and potatoes between plates. Drizzle pork with sauce and serve.